,Recommended,403700,27603297,"Posted: 25 November, 2016",all,Wackerly,"I feel like people don't give this game enough time before reviewing it. That part where you put hats on (you know, the main part of the game) is just that: *part* of the game. In itself, it's simple in concept, yet challenging and silly. You run around, trying to catch a hat falling from the sky onto your head. Except there's more than one person on the screen and they all look identical to begin with. And sometimes it's not just a hat that falls from the sky, it's a refrigerator that will kill you upon impact. Or a stop sign that will kill you upon impact. Or both. Don't forget, if you get far enough, you'll catch a wizard's hat instead, causing him to curse you with a negative effect you have to deal with on the next stage. If you win that stage, you get a bonus, be it double hats or an extra life. Eventually, you can buy a gift from the gift shop. THIS reveals the true nature of this game; as you collect gifts, you play a different minigame to acquire a buttload of hats. Get enough hats, then something strange happens (I won't spoil it for you), and you must seek answers from within the minigames. Eventually you end up taking out a final boss and cueing the end credits. If you didn't realize that this game had a final boss, then it is my opinion that you had no right to review. It doesn't take long to get from start to finish; you can do it in a couple of hours. Once you realize what's really going on, the game has a very meta-game feeling to it where the hat-collecting is a small part of the whole, even though that's literally 90% of the gameplay. That's why I nominate it for the ""Game Within a Game"" Award for the 2016 Steam Awards."
